1320–1375":"1320–1375","1330–1370":"1330–1370","1422":"1422","1466":"1466","1388":"1388","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","about 1374":"about 1374","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Bray, Berkshire, England":"Bray, Berkshire, England","Bray, Maidenhead, Berkshire, England":"Bray, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Norreys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Norris  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Norris","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Middle English <i>norreis</i>, <i>noreis</i>, <i>norais</i> ‘northerner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>noreis</i>), used both of Norwegians and of inhabitants of northern England and Scotland.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Norreis</i>, derived from <i>norreis</i> ‘northerner’."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe'